      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Having a Great Detox'' (Thursday Styles, March 29):</p>
        <p>I am angered by your article. Addiction is a fatal disease. It tears families apart. Catering to celebrity chic undermines the struggle that most families go through.</p>
        <p>Addiction is neither fashion nor a fad. It is a painful, daily, lifelong, life-altering disease suffered not only by the addict but also by his or her family. Would cancer treatment centers present themselves as day spas?</p>
        <p>Celebrities who struggle with disease can raise awareness of that disease or draw attention to the need for research money. Sadly, some celebrities have twisted the definition of ''rehab'' into a vehicle for media coverage. No wonder insurance companies are denying coverage for addicts, though addiction is a disease like cancer or diabetes.</p>
        <p>It's ''cool'' to go into rehab? Shame on these celebrities. Shame on their fans for admiring them. Shame on the media that glamorize them. Shame on the treatment centers that cater to them.</p>
        <p>Joanne Clark  Norwalk, Conn., March 31, 2007</p>
      </block>
